


@{ViewBag.Title = "Mayor announces &pound;5.1m for transport improvements in Hammersmith and Fulham ";}
        
        

<div class="r">
    <div class="headline-container plain">
        <h1>Mayor announces &pound;5.1m for transport improvements in Hammersmith and Fulham </h1>
        <div class="content-page-press-release">
        16 November 2007
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="main-and-aside r">
    <div class="main" role="main">

    <div class="article-teaser">
        The Mayor of London today announced &pound;5.1m of funding for Hammersmith and Fulham to spend on local transport improvements to make the borough safer, greener and more accessible.
        
    </div>



<div class="pull-quote">
        <div class="quote-body">"This &pound;5.1m investment will go towards directly improving transport for people in Hammersmith and Fulham"</div>
        <div class="quote-footer">
            <div class="quotee-name">Peter Hendy</div>
            <div class="quotee-job-title">London's Transport Commissioner</div>
        </div>
</div>

 <div class="on-this-page">
<div class="pullquote right">
                        <p>
                            This &pound;5.1m investment will go towards directly improving transport for people in Hammersmith and Fulham
                            
                        </p>
                    </div>
                
            
            
            <p>
<p>The &pound;5.1m funding includes &pound;725,000 for the London Cycle Network+ for more cycle lanes and better facilities for cyclists in Hammersmith and Fulham, &pound;870,000 to strengthen the bridge on Hammersmith Road above the District Line, &pound;200,000 for 20mph zones and &pound;100,000 to improve Fulham Town Centre with better pavements and signage.</p>
<p>The funding is part of the record-breaking five-year &pound;792m programme for local transport schemes included in the Transport for London (TfL)&nbsp;&pound;10bn Investment Programme.</p>
<p>Mayor of London, Ken Livingstone said: "This new &pound;5.1m investment in local transport schemes will make the daily journeys of people in Hammersmith and Fulham, safer, greener and more accessible, whether they are travelling by public transport, by car, on foot or by bike.</p>
<p>"Thanks to extra investment in local transport schemes, cycling has increased by 83 per cent since 2000 and more than 1600 school travel plans have been approved which encourage and enable more children and their parents to walk to school."&nbsp; </p>
<h2>Local transport improvements</h2>
<p>London's Transport Commissioner, Peter Hendy, said: "This &pound;5.1m investment will go towards directly improving transport for people in Hammersmith and Fulham.</p>
<p>"Local people feel strongly about transport in their area and this funding will make a real difference to their experience each day.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>
<p>"The investment will fund both large and small projects that will improve bus journeys and access to public transport, reduce congestion, improve the environment and promote a healthier lifestyle. </p>
<p>"This funding is an important part of our wider programme of spending in the boroughs to make improvements to local transport."</p>
<p>Projects funded in Hammersmith and Fulham for 2008/09 include:</p>
<ul>
<li>&pound;725,000 for the London Cycle Network+ </li>
<li>&pound;200,000 for 20mph zones to improve safety in local streets </li>
<li>&pound;870,000 for Phase 2 of the scheme to strengthen the bridge on Hammersmith Road above the District line </li>
<li>&pound;100,000 to continue work to improve the environment in Fulham Town Centre in 2005/6 and 2007/8. This will include repaving, renewing and de-cluttering street furniture, such as railings and benches, and resurfacing to meet accessibility standards and better signage </li>
<li>&pound;30,000 for measures to improve bus services and journey times, including a new westbound bus lane on Olympia Bridge and conditions for cyclists </li>
<li>&pound;30,000 to promote campaigns that encourage greener travel, including: 'Bike Week', 'In town without my car day', 'National Liftshare Day' and 'Walking Works' - to promote walking to work</li></ul>
<p>
<hr>

<p>
<p><strong>Notes for editors:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Each year the borough prepares a Local Implementation Plan to demonstrate how they propose to implement the Mayor's Transport Strategy locally. While TfL awards funding for individual schemes, project delivery is the responsibility of the borough </li>
<li>Priorities for the Local Implementation Plans include: 
<ul type="circle">
<li>Improving road safety </li>
<li>Improving bus journey times and reliability </li>
<li>Relieving traffic congestion and improving journey time reliability </li>
<li>Improving the working of parking and loading arrangements </li>
<li>Improving accessibility for all on the transport network </li>
<li>Encouraging walking and cycling </li>
<li>Bringing transport infrastructure into a good state of repair</li></ul></li>
<li>Below is an allocation breakdown of Local Implementation Plan funding for Hammersmith and Fulham for 2008/09:</li></ul>
<p>Principal road renewals&nbsp;- &pound;1,528,000<br>Bridge strengthening&nbsp;- &pound;870,000<br>Local safety schemes -&nbsp;&pound;420,000<br>20mph zones&nbsp;- &pound;200,000<br>Education, training and publicity&nbsp;- &pound;55,000<br>Walking&nbsp;- &pound;100,000<br>Cycling&nbsp;- &pound;165,000<br>London Cycle Network+&nbsp;- &pound;725,000<br>Bus stop accessibility&nbsp;- &pound;90,000<br>Bus priority&nbsp;- &pound;535,000<br>School Travel Plans&nbsp;- &pound;246,000<br>Travel awareness&nbsp;- &pound;30,000<br>Local area accessibility&nbsp;- &pound;40,000<br>Parallel initiatives&nbsp;- &pound;140,000<br><strong>Total&nbsp;- &pound;5,144,000</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>A School Travel Plan is a package of measures, tailored to the needs of individual schools to deliver alternative transport methods for the school run.&nbsp;The aim of a school travel plan is to reduce single occupancy car journeys to school, reduce congestion and increase safety around schools </li>
<li>The London Cycle Network+ is funded by TfL. It will provide 900km of safer, faster cycle routes through the Capital. It's due to be finished by 2010 and is one of TfL's major investments&nbsp;</li></ul>

     

        
        
        
